{{Other uses|Detention center (disambiguation){{!}}Detention center}}
{{Orphan|date=December 2013}}

[[Image:Cells detention centers 3.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Cells without (left) and with (right) Detention Centers]]
A '''nucleolar detention center (DC)''' is a region of the [[Cell (biology)|cell]] in which certain [[protein]]s are [[Nucleolus#Sequestration of proteins|temporarily detained]] in periods of [[Cellular stress response|cellular stress]].<ref name="jacobmboc">{{cite journal |vauthors=Jacob MD, Audas TE, Uniacke J, Trinkle-Mulcahy L, Lee S |title=Environmental cues induce a long noncoding RNA-dependent remodeling of the nucleolus |journal=Mol Biol Cell |volume=24|issue=18 |pages=2943–53 |year=2013|pmid=23904269 |doi=10.1091/mbc.E13-04-0223 |pmc=3771955}}</ref> DCs are absent from cells under normal culture conditions, but form in response to specific environmental triggers, such as [[Acidosis|low extracellular pH]] or [[heat shock|high temperature]], when [[long noncoding RNA]]s are induced from regions of [[Intergenic region|intergenic DNA]].<ref name="jacobmboc" /><ref name="audasmc">{{cite journal |vauthors=Audas TE, Jacob MD, Lee S |title=Immobilization of proteins in the nucleolus by ribosomal intergenic spacer noncoding RNA |journal=Mol Cell |volume=45|issue=2 |pages=145–57 |year=2012|pmid=    22284675 |doi=10.1016/j.molcel.2011.12.012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Prasanth KV |title=Policing cells under stress: noncoding RNAs capture proteins in nucleolar detention centers |journal=Mol Cell |volume=45|issue=2 |pages=141–2 |year=2012|pmid=22284672 |doi=10.1016/j.molcel.2012.01.005}}</ref> The detention of numerous proteins in DCs is believed to reduce metabolic activity and promote survival under unfavorable conditions.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Audas TE, Jacob MD, Lee S |title=The nucleolar detention pathway: a cellular strategy for regulating molecular networks |journal=Cell Cycle |volume=11|issue=11 |pages=2059–62 |year=2012|pmid=22580471 |doi=10.4161/cc.20140| pmc=3368857}}</ref>
DCs form at the center of [[Nucleolus|nucleoli]] and therefore disrupt the normal organization of these organelles. The structural remodeling that ensues leaves [[Nucleolus|nucleoli]] unable to sustain their primary function, [[Nucleolus#Function and ribosome assembly|ribosomal biogenesis]]. Therefore, the formation of DCs is thought to convert nucleoli from “ribosome factories” to “prisons for proteins”.<ref name="jacobmboc" />

